data.title: Voice of Flamenco
authors: Contributors to Dress Up! Time Princess Wiki
data.meta_description: Voice of Flamenco is a My Collection set with 16 pieces of clothing. The set style is Sensible and Noble. It is one of the featured sets for the Flamenco Night event. The reward for completing this set is 100 and a Story Kingdom Set Look. Hairstyle: Alegria Headwear: Song of Freedom Hairpin...
data.text:
In cheerful flamenco style, this dance piece is fast-paced, with such energetic guitar music, that even the dancers have a smile on their faces.

— Alegria

A type of Flamenco music. Most of these songs come from traditional rhythmic flamenco music, which later evolved into purely melodic performances.

— Song of Freedom

Some believe it originated in Galicia and developed from traditional Christmas carols.

— Farruca

In the second half of the 19th century, popular songs were mixed with flamenco, giving birth to the style known today as Malaguena.

— Malaguena

It is one of the oldest forms of flamenco singing, and consists of the singer singing without any accompaniment.

— Tonas

Flamenco is the art of fusing dance, song and guitar. Flamenco is a free and liberating dance, often performed in dozens of styles. Join me in this dance and learn more about the art of Flamenco!

— Voice of Flamenco

Cante grande, another main stylistic family of Flamenco, is darker in its sentiment, with themes such as loss, anguish, despair and death.

— Cante Grande

Cante intermedio is one of the main stylistic families of Flamenco.

— Cante Intermedio

Cante chico is another one of the main stylistic families of Flamenco, played in a relaxed and light-hearted style. Its themes often include happiness and love.

— Cante Chico

The deep singing style is usually considered to be of Andalusian origin.

— Jondo

This is a form of Flamenco singing, often in a deep and solemn style.

— Seguiriya

Interestingly, this form of singing does not require guitar accompaniment, only simple percussion sound. The birth of the style may be associated with workers who sang with hammers and anvils as accompaniment.

— Martinete

The source of this Flamenco rhythm usually comes from clapping, rattles, or wooden box drums.

— Compas

Originating from southern Andalusia, it is one of the most classic flamenco styles. The strong rhythm and sad lyrics convey the pain and passion of the singers, while the dancers are often solemn and grave.

— Solea

In the 16th century, the art from Cuba was brought to Spain, where it was fused with Flamenco, giving birth to performance forms like the Guajira.

— Guajira
